{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RNa1Ceka4JYVbubAdWpc5X","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created successfully.\n\n**Story 5.2: Verification Runtime Integration** created at:\n`/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-2-verification-runtime-integration.md`\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 5.2\n- Story Key: 5-2-verification-runtime-integration\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n- Sprint status yaml NOT modified (per user instruction)\n\n**Key findings during analysis:**\n- Most of the code for this story already exists from Epic 2. The verify prompt template (`src/templates/verify-prompt.ts`) already has `Step 3.5: Observability Check After Each Command`. The parser (`src/modules/verify/parser.ts`) already has `parseObservabilityGaps()`. The orchestrator (`src/modules/verify/index.ts`) already calls these and populates `VerifyResult` with gap counts and runtime coverage.\n- The primary deliverable is updating `patches/verify/story-verification.md` to include observability evidence instructions, plus writing tests to prove the existing end-to-end flow works.\n- 7 ACs total: 5 tagged `cli-verifiable`, 2 tagged `integration-required` (AC #6 requires a live observability stack, AC #7 requires end-to-end verification workflow execution).\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity in epic definition:** The epic's AC #2 says \"verify-prompt.ts is updated\" but the template already contains the observability instructions from Epic 2. I interpreted this as \"verify the template already works correctly\" rather than \"make new changes,\" since the code is already there. The story's AC #2 reflects this as a confirmation/regression-test task.\n- **Workaround applied:** The workflow instructs updating sprint-status.yaml to `ready-for-dev`, but the user explicitly prohibited this. The story file is marked `ready-for-dev` in its own status field but sprint-status.yaml still shows `backlog`.\n- **Risk — thin story:** Since most code already exists, this story is largely a patch update + test writing exercise. There's a risk the dev agent may over-engineer or create unnecessary code changes. The dev notes section explicitly calls out \"do NOT rewrite\" for existing components.\n- **Observation:** This is the last story in Epic 5 and the last story in the sprint. No downstream dependencies."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1ad1399d02e13597 (use SendMessage with to: 'a1ad1399d02e13597' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 72393\ntool_uses: 40\nduration_ms: 168501</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"63766b2b-ee05-46af-a819-a3f0370845d2","uuid":"d66be16b-249d-4ec7-9a40-7108bc619590","timestamp":"2026-03-21T06:31:48.742Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-create-story for story 5-2-verification-runtime-integration. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`","agentId":"a1ad1399d02e13597","content":[{"type":"te