{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FACXhGTPVySCDoGGQ2PkXo","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## WHY\n     2→\n     3→Stories were marked \"done\" with no proof artifact, or with proofs that only\n     4→grepped source code instead of exercising the feature from the user's\n     5→perspective. This patch mandates black-box proof documents, docker exec evidence,\n     6→verification tags per AC, and test coverage targets — preventing regressions\n     7→from being hidden behind source-level assertions.\n     8→(FR33, FR36, NFR20)\n     9→\n    10→## Verification Requirements\n    11→\n    12→Every story must produce a **black-box proof** — evidence that the feature works from the user's perspective, NOT from reading source code.\n    13→\n    14→### Proof Standard\n    15→\n    16→- Proof document at `verification/<story-key>-proof.md`\n    17→- Each AC gets a `## AC N:` section with `docker exec` commands and captured output\n    18→- Evidence must come from running the installed CLI/tool, not from grepping source\n    19→- `[FAIL]` = AC failed with evidence showing what went wrong\n    20→- `[ESCALATE]` = AC genuinely cannot be automated (last resort — try everything first)\n    21→\n    22→### Verification Tags\n    23→\n    24→For each AC, append a tag indicating verification approach:\n    25→- `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` — default. Can be verified via CLI commands in a Docker container.\n    26→- `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` — requires external systems not available in the test environment (e.g., paid third-party APIs, physical hardware). This is rare — most things including workflows, agent sessions, and multi-step processes CAN be verified in Docker.\n    27→\n    28→**Do not over-tag.** Workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, slash commands, and agent behavior are all verifiable via `docker exec ... claude --print`. Only tag `integration-required` when there is genuinely no automated path.\n    29→\n    30→### Observability Evidence\n    31→\n    32→After each `docker exec` command, query the observability backend for log events from the last 30 seconds:\n    33→\n    34→```bash\n    35→curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n    36→```\n    37→\n    38→- If log entries are returned, note the count in the AC section as runtime observability evidence.\n    39→- If **zero events** are returned, include `[OBSERVABILITY GAP]` in the AC section:\n    40→  `[OBSERVABILITY GAP] No log events detected for this user interaction`\n    41→- Every AC should produce at least one log entry when exercised. Gaps indicate silent code paths.\n    42→- If the observability backend is **not reachable** (connection refused, timeout), report\n    43→  \"observability check skipped — backend not reachable\" as a warning and do NOT fail the verification.\n    44→  The functional verification result stands on its own.\n    45→\n    46→This ensures proof documents include both functional evidence (`docker exec` output) and\n    47→observability evidence (log query results or `[OBSERVABILITY GAP]` tags) for each AC.\n    48→\n    49→The VictoriaLogs query pattern matches `verify-prompt.ts` Step 3.5 — see that template for\n    50→the full observability check instructions used by the automated verifier agent.\n    51→\n    52→### Testing Requirements\n    53→\n    54→- Unit tests for all new/changed code\n    55→- Coverage target: 100% of new/changed lines\n    56→- No skipped tests without justification\n    57→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01St1ZX8VZKJ5rWiDeuqc1Kp","session_id":"63766b2b-ee05-46af-a819-a3f0370845d2","uuid":"faaaabce-2348-4936-abf1-4af2da8bdefc","timestamp":"2026-03-21T06:36:56.952Z"}
